<font color="#FF0000">SPARROWHAWK AND DOC</font><br>
<tt>Thu Sep 25  6:06:52 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Sparrowhawk,<br><br>
That was a powerful story. Thanks for sharing it! You are fortunate to have had closure on some of the stuff, and hopefully it is now just a bad memory, instead of an endless loop of timewarp reality. It is funny how that works. I have several closed loops that don't quit. One of them I recently identified with a distinct part of my behavior. Sometimes it must be like East LA. I have never been to East LA, but there are times I know I could feel very much at home there, in the dark. Most of my waking time in 'Nam was spent under the cover of darkness. I am at peace in the dark, and what goes with it, because it feeds the hungry timewarp loops at a very basic level. I still seek danger, the fight, combat, in many ways. It provides the rush that counteracts the deep depression that rides along for the show. Very borderline socially acceptable and perhaps some not so socially acceptable &quot;self medication&quot; with situations! HA! At least I have no beef with the authorities, and they have none with me. My intellect keeps me out of trouble, and has done so for as long as I remember. I have been told that I am one of the lucky ones. From what I see in myself now, and in others, they are right. I also cycle with this stuff. Right now, I am enjoying one of the longest relatively stable periods I have ever experienced since 'Nam, 6 months! I have a hearing with the &quot;admin&quot; side of the VA on Friday. That's going to be a trip in my head if I don't prepare for it now. I don't want to get triggered and check out. I am having too much fun enjoying life, but sometimes there is no choice, and it takes over again. Combat inside my head, too. As my top shrink says, &quot;Wicked Sucky!&quot; <br><br>
Doc,<br><br>
Thanks for your advice and pep talk! I started serious therapy for PTSD two years ago, and have over 80-90 therapy sessions under my belt so far. I do speak openly about it  now when the situation is right for it and people understand. There is still the social stigma of 'mental illness' and the discrimination people still practice. There is also a lot of misinformation out there. I still get the post office / uzi story. It all hurts, a lot. 
